om the WordPress.com TOS and are released under a Creative Common 3.0 license. That was more like what I expected and didnât seem to jive with what I was seeing in the footer. So I did a little more searching. Pretty soon I found this:  In the search results, I could see that the line that was bothering me is actually a pretty reasonable bit of template language: All content copyright {{@blog.title}} Â© 2013 [â¦] This was a simple matter of defaults causing accidental messaging. See when you create a blog on Ghost, the default name of the blog is âGhostâ. Then the footer is outputting the blog name (Ghost) as the copyright holder.1 If I had taken the time to set my blog name to âAlex Kingâ, then the footer message would have read âcopyright Alex Kingâ. This is a case of several things coming together to say something they didnât mean. Be careful with your defaults! Your messaging is important and if youâre not careful it can say something you didnât intend.     Iâm not a lawyer, but I believe this really isnât an accurate copyright statement. Copyright is owned by a person or entity; the name of a blog isnât something that can own copyright (unless it is also the name of a person or entity).Â â©   \'>Alex King: Ghost and Accidental Messaging</a></li><li><a class=\'rsswidget\' href=\'http://blog.akismet.com/2013/12/27/2013-in-review/\' title=\'As 2013 draws to a close, we at Akismet would like to let you know just what weâve been up to â and, of course, wish you a very happy holiday season. For the abridged version, weâve prepared a nifty infographic illustrating the year that was:   We reached an incredible milestone this year in catching our 100-billionth spam comment. And weâre already fast approaching our 115-billionth. The levels of spam weâre seeing and catching have increased dramatically over the past year. In fact, when compared with 2012 numbers (as seen in last yearâs post), each month in 2013 experienced an average year-over-year increase of more than 70%, asÂ theÂ following chart shows:  On average, we are currently catching aroundÂ 200 million spam comments every day, which is about 80 million moreÂ than our daily average this time last year. Thatâs over 8,000,000 per hour, or over 2,000 per second. For the year, we averaged over 120 million spam comments per day â a year-over-year jump of over 50 million. On December 21, we set a new record zappingÂ 245 million spam comments in just 24 hours. While spam themes and schemes are always changing, knockoff fashion-goods spam (which we talked about in last yearâs post) dominated 2013. Even more troubling is the rising trend of these spammers using hacked sites to deliver payloads. You may have seen these before, where links point to individual pages that include an extension (like â.aspâ). We suspect that disenchanted SEO spammers are using this strategy in response to new policies by Google.Â Instead of simply posting comments with links to their own sites, theyâve moved to hacking vulnerable sites and launching buffer pages. Since the launch of Googleâs Penguin 2.1 back in October, we have actually seen a significant increase in daily spam averages. Other themes of comment spam have certainly developed and intensified over the last 12 months (spell casters, anyone?), but these are merely blips on the radar compared to the knockoff-fashion variety. Here are some recent examples of sites that Akismet intercepted:      Beyond our usual spam fighting activities, we have also started reaching out to other UGC services to see where, based on our vast pool of spam data, we can help in identifying spam troubling their own communities. We hope to expand that initiative in the coming year, and include hosts in the conversation as well. In 2014 you can also expect more educational anti-spam projects (including webinars), more frequent and insightful blog content, enhanced support documentation, and an increase in developer-friendly initiatives. And, of course, even stronger spam protection. A sincere Happy Holidays to you and yours, The Akismet Team (Alex, Mark, Eoin, Anthony, Chris F., Valerie, Chris R., Greg, Dan, and Nick)   \'>Akismet: Our 2013 In Review</a></li><li><a class=\'rsswidget\' href=\'http://wordpress.tv/2013/12/27/tomas-puig-design-and-development-trends-in-wordpress/\' title=\'    \'>WordPress.tv: Tomas Puig: Design And Development Trends In WordPress</a></li><li><a class=\'rsswidget\' href=\'http://torquemag.io/will-2014-be-the-year-of-wordpress-tuck-ins-and-roll-ups/\' title=\'Most WordPress businesses are very young (Crowd Favorite was one of, if not the first in 2007). As these businesses mature and realize what is needed of them to take the next steps, consolidation often looks like a saner route than continuing to build. Especially for technical founders that arenât as interested in managing the necessary business infrastructure (I count myself in this group). This post is part of the thread: Crowd Favorite â an ongoing story on this site. View the thread timeline for more context on this post. #\'>Alex King: Will 2014 Be the Year of WordPress Tuck-ins and Roll-ups?</a></li></ul></div>','no'),(10945,'_site_transient_browser_8b7535adeddc223aa9c8b2b378cdf189','a:9:{s:8:\"platform\";s:9:\"Macintosh\";s:4:\"name\";s:6:\"Chrome\";s:7:\"version\";s:12:\"31.0.1650.63\";s:10:\"update_url\";s:28:\"http://www.google.com/chrome\";s:7:\"img_src\";s:49:\"http://s.wordpress.org/images/browsers/chrome.png\";s:11:\"img_src_ssl\";s:48:\"https://wordpress.org/images/browsers/chrome.png\";s:15:\"current_version\";s:2:\"18\";s:7:\"upgrade\";b:0;s:8:\"insecure\";b:0;}','yes'),(6765,'wpseo_rss','a:1:{s:8:\"rssafter\";s:53:\"The post %%POSTLINK%% appeared first on %%BLOGLINK%%.\";}','yes'),(5832,'theme_mods_thejsj8','a:2:{i:0;b:0;s:18:\"nav_menu_locations\";a:2:{s:8:\"main-nav\";i:21;s:12:\"footer-links\";i:0;}}','yes'),(5833,'theme_switched','','yes'),(5834,'nav_menu_options','a:2