 the color in equal ways. Even do the attribution of each color to each type of interaction is relative (red to comment, blue to messages...) isÂ arbitrary, the rest is not.\r\n\r\nThe software also permits forÂ differentÂ filters on the type of content to beÂ established by theÂ differentÂ types of interactions.\r\n<h3>Data Mining</h3>\r\nData mining also played a crucial role in the making of this piece. The data was taken from theÂ FacebookÂ feature, Download your data. A PHP script was written that entered all this data into a MySQL database. An already functioning script (<a href=\"http://simplehtmldom.sourceforge.net/\">simple_html_dom.php</a>) was adapted for the information pulled out. There were four tables that were used for the data: friends, posts, comments and messages. While this sounds simple, it probably took as much time as any other part of the project.\r\n\r\nI also made a short lived website where anyone could upload theirÂ FacebookÂ data and make similar visualizations.Â Unfortunately, because of my lack of programming skills, it had a memory leak. My web hosting company shut it down after a few days.\r\n\r\n<!-- <img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-213\" title=\"friendsonfacebook\" alt=\"\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/friendsonfacebook-300x179.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"179\" /> -->','Facebook Data Visualization','','publish','closed','closed','','my-friends-on-facebook','','','2013-05-24 15:49:33','2013-05-24 15:49:33','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?post_type=piece&#038;p=208',15,'piece','',0),(209,1,'2011-10-13 23:55:11','2011-10-13 23:55:11','In thisÂ interactiveÂ data visualization, the visual information of the paintings at MoMA was extracted (through the use of Â <a title=\"Image Plot\" href=\" http://lab.softwarestudies.com/p/imageplot.html\" target=\"_blank\">ImagePlot</a>) and visualized through different categories. Hue, Saturation and Brightness were extracted by the standard deviation and Median and visualized in a timeline. Many filters are available in which certain sets of information can be accessed orÂ highlighted.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/paintings.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-211\" title=\"paintings\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/paintings-1024x481.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"481\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThis is a very simple and effective way ofÂ visualizingÂ data, but also a very different way of thinking about art. What if art became something to be analyzedÂ statisticallyÂ rather than verbally? What data could we extract from art? What trends and patterns do we find in the work?\r\n\r\nAnÂ interestingÂ part of this process was understanding the difference between theÂ aestheticÂ value of the visualization in contrast to it functional value. The image below Â utilizes the same data as the final piece (this image came before the final project) and while it wasÂ certainlyÂ visuallyÂ interesting, it was very hard to comprehend and didn\'t actually say much about the actual data. This is a problem, or a spectrum, inherent to the practice of graphic design. The designer must choose whether the scope of the project is formal/aestheticÂ or wether it is functional/clear/invisible/pragmatic. Personally, I feel that the latter is more important as a work of dataÂ visualization. DataÂ visualizationÂ is about communicating ideas, not creatingÂ interestingÂ visuals. This is clear in this particular project. This is a pretty cool visual (below) though!\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Triangles1.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-718\" title=\"Triangles\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Triangles1-1024x301.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"301\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Statistical Painting Analysis','','publish','closed','closed','','statistical-painting-analysis',