d music, color, human language, images, videos, timeâ¦ into binary code. If there is a new universal language, why do we still hold on to the impossibility of translation? This translation into binary code is always limited and is always a sort of betrayal. Seeing the <em>Mona Lisa </em>at the Louvre is not the same as seeing it through a computer screen, yet that doesnât stop us from doing it. Hearing Beethovenâs Symphony no. 5 played in an .mp3 is not the same as hearing it played by the New York Orchestra at the Carnegie Hall, yet we still listen to it through our Ipod. We also translate this information into different formats (.mp3 to .ogg, .jpeg to .png) on a daily basis.\r\n\r\nThe next step in these translations it the translation of information into, not just different formats, but different types of information. The digital realm permits a seamless translation from music to colour, words to image, and video to Mandarin. These are all possibilities that might result in a beautiful treason.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Is everything translatable?','','inherit','open','open','','300-revision-2','','','2011-11-15 22:00:31','2011-11-15 22:00:31','',300,'http://thejsj.com/2011/300-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(305,1,'2011-11-01 02:29:57','2011-11-01 02:29:57','<article></article><article>Welcome to the Portfolio Page of Jorge Silva Jetter. This is a space in the web solely dedicated to show some of my work. This is a very simple site, but with some very special <del>features</del>.The work in this site span from some very simple design, to some experimental stuff, to some complex programming on some of the sites. Some of the work is for clients, some is personal and some is NGO\'s and non-profits.In the \"A bit More\" section you can finds someÂ straightforwardÂ facts about the person writing this. You can also contact me several ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<h3 class=\"facts\">You can get in touch with me at...</h3>\r\n<div id=\"contact\">Email: jorge.silva@thejsj.com\