ds/2012/07/0.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(809,1,'2012-07-30 03:37:27','2012-07-30 03:37:27','<em>For my monument, I wish to question the nature of the monument. A monument is a space designed for remembering. It is always permanent. The monument is part of the sedentary nature of human beings. Yet, what happens when we must make a monument for nomads? What happens when we must make a monument for a people that are transparent?</em>\n\n<em>We must build a monument that destroys itself.</em>\n\n<em>I intend to build a monument grand in scale made of wax. My giant piece of wax will move, just as the Roma did for thousands of years. Inscribed into my monument will be the words âA Monument to the Roma, A people in movementâ.</em>\n\n<em>Unfortunately, merely by accident, my giant piece of was will grow a wick, turning this endearing monument into a more common object, a candle; A candle made monumental by itâs scale. More unfortunate is the possibly that this beautiful and simple monument might be mysteriously lit.</em>\n\n<iframe src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/afpF55sVrCA\" frameborder=\"0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\"></iframe>\n\nThis project was realized as part of my graduate workshop, in Spring 2012. The goal of the project was to study, understand and immerseÂ yourselfÂ in a specific culture. I chose the Roma, also know as Gypsies because of my longÂ fascinationÂ with their culture, music and way of life.\n\nOne of the goals of this project was to build a monument to this culture. I created a nomadic monument, a monument that would destroy itself and through this process question the nature of the monument as a creation of cultures tied to a specific place, but possibly alien to a nomadic culture such as the Roma, spread through out the world.\n\nThrough this project, I ventured the treacherousÂ waters of the moving image,','Monument to the Roma','','inherit','open','open','','807-autosave','','','2012-07-30 03:37:27','2012-07-30 03:37:27','',807,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/807-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(810,1,'2012-04-25 03:44:53','2012-04-25 03:44:53','<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/48664563\" width=\"600\" height=\"350\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe> <p><a href=\"http://vimeo.com/48664563\">Book Making</a> from <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/user13278058\">Jorge Silva-Jetter</a> on <a href=\"http://vimeo.com\">Vimeo</a>.</p>\r\n\r\nThrough my exploration of the Roma culture, I decided to make a container for my loose pages thatÂ resembledÂ my earlier monument. The book, in a way, makes itself. I am only a custodian of the process, carrying it out as I see fit, but the final result has no relation to my own creations.\r\n\r\nHere are some of the pages on the book dealing with my explorations of the Roma people:\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\"]','A Book for the Roma','','publish','closed','closed','','a-book-for-the-roma','','','2013-05-30 18:47:07','2013-05-30 18:47:07','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?post_type=piece&#038;p=810',18,'piece','',0),(811,1,'2012-07-30 04:00:01','2012-07-30 04:00:01','[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1397,1398,1399,1400\"]\r\n\r\nI decided to explore the issue of the algorithm through interaction. The interactive piece removes many of the controls a user typically has in an interactive experience and renders the absolute power of the algorithm. The user is annoyed, frustrated and mad over theÂ decisionsÂ undertaken by the algorithm, but the user has no choice except abandoing the experience altogether.\r\n\r\nIn a world increasingly dominated by technology it becomes increasingly harder to escape the realm dominated by the algorithm.','The Algorithm','','publish','closed','closed','','the-algorithm','','','2013-05-30 18:53:52','2013-05-30 18:53:52','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?post_type=piece&#038;p=811',20,'piece','',0),(812,1,'2012-07-30 03:52:44','2012-07-30 03:52:44','','AsOtXAYCAAA9Avv','','inherit','open','open',''