 href=\"http://www.okaygreat.com/\">http://www.okaygreat.com/</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://designtaxi.com/\">http://designtaxi.com/</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://datavisualization.ch/\">http://datavisualization.ch/</a>','Home','','publish','open','open','','home','','','2012-11-01 16:22:04','2012-11-01 16:22:04','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?page_id=843',0,'page','',0),(817,1,'2012-08-23 14:16:40','2012-08-23 14:16:40','It all started with Lev. At theÂ beginningÂ of my short stay in grad school, I knew I would have to come up with an idea for my thesis. This sounded a bit overwhelming. What could I work on for two year without getting bored? At some point, I decided to read \"The Language of New Media\". I felt I was reading a the HolyÂ Scriptures. What captured me about the book was that, in a world dominated by technology, few people were talking about how to integrate technology and design, how to make work that was in sync with our times, how to think about new media in a way that understood the increasing role of technology in our socities and work. I found a lot of answers in this book.\r\n\r\nI decided pretty quickly that this is what my thesis would be about.Â Specifically, I wanted to deal with databases. How do you design for databases? After a short time as a web designer, I became increasingly disillusioned by the practice of web design. Web design, as a field, was concerned mostly with the outer look of this piece and took very little concern with the content, the narrative behind what was being presented. I seemed to me that it was only concerned with the outer shell of it all. The database, Lev said, was the cultural form of our time. This is what my thesis was going to be about.\r\n\r\nFor me it was quite clear. Narrative was a thing of the past. Narrative was out, databases were in. Anyone who thought a narrative approach to design was \"the way to go\", was simply a 20th centuryÂ dinosaur.','A Thesis Tragedy, Part 1 \"Oh Lev, I love you\"','','pending','open','open','','a-thesis-tragedy-part1','','','2012-08-27 16:16:37','2012-08-27 16:16:37','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?p=817',0,'post','',0),(818,1,'2012-08-23 14:16:12','2012-08-23 14:16:12','It all started with Lev. At theÂ beginningÂ of my short stay in grad school, I knew I would have to come up with an idea for my thesis. This sounded a bit overwhelming. What could I work on for two year without getting bored? At some point, I decided to read \"The Language of New Media\". I felt I was reading a the HolyÂ Scriptures. What captured me about the book was that, in a world dominated by technology, few people were talking about how to integrate technology and design, how to make work that was in sync with our times, how to think about new media in a way that understood the increasing role of technology in our socities and work. I found a lot of answers in this book.\n\nI decided pretty quickly that this is what my thesis would be about.Â Specifically, I wanted to deal with databases. How do you design for databases? After a short time as a web designer, I became increasingly disillusioned by the practice of web design. Web design, as a field, was concerned mostly with the outer look of this piece and took very little concern with the content, the narrative behind what was being presented. I seemed to me that it was only concerned with the outer shell of it all. The database, Lev said, was the cultural form of our time. This is what my thesis was going to be about.\n\nFor me it was quite clear. Narrative was a thing of the past. Narrative was out, databases were in. Anyone who thought a narrative approach to design was \"\"','A Thesis Tragedy, Part 1 \"Oh Lev, I love you\"','','inherit','open','open','','817-revision','','','2012-08-23 14:16:12','2012-08-23 14:16:12','',817,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/817-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(819,1,'2012-08-23 14:39:20','2012-08-23 14:39:20','After my brief (and perhaps not so brief) falling in love with Lev, I now had to actually come up with a thesis. It was all very clear in my head, but apparently nowhere else. I now had to explain my thesis idea to many people, many times. No one really understood what I was talking about. Was it me, or were these people just too 20th century for my forward-looking ideas? (yes, there was a bit of arrogance in all these statements!). I tried to explain to people that I wanted to design for databases. I explained to them how they worked in the web for example. \"So you want to design website?\". \"So you want to make templates?\". \"So you want to automate design?\". \"Is this an Artificial Intelligence project?\". At the end, after many attempts, it just became \"This doesn\'t make any sense!\".\r\n\r\nI now had a new challenge, \"How do I explain this to my classmates and professors?\". More importantly, the problem became another one, one that I was able to recognize myself. How can I establish a problem that is more in tune with graphic design? After a while, I felt that the problem I was proposing was not so much of a design problem and that the reason why no one was really understanding what I was trying to say was that it was not a problem that could be easilyÂ addressedÂ by graphic design. The solution was to fine tune my problem statement to designers.\r\n\r\nI then thought about how it was that I was going to accomplish this in terms of design. My conclusion, after a long time of thinking, was systems and rules. If there is a lot of data that needs to be designed and presented, the solution to a new approach to design more in sync withÂ technologyÂ and the way technology works is focusing, not on a single event of design, but on systems and rules. I would establish systems and rules that would address multiple contents.\r\n\r\nIn response to the monotony of web design and other types of design \"systems\", my systems and rules would be dynamic, they would be open. The same content could be shown in different ways according toÂ computationallyÂ open rules. Things such as randomness and encoding became very important parts of my ideas. As an example I created a \"dynamic\" poster. This poster has one design but many different outputs.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster2-e1333393857788.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-721\" title=\"SystemPoster2\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster2-e1333393857788-199x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"199\" height=\"300\" /></a>Â <a href=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster3-e1333393749822.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-722\" title=\"SystemPoster3\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster3-e1333393749822-199x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"199\" height=\"300\" /></a>Â <a href=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster-e1333393815354.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-720\" title=\"SystemPoster\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster-e1333393815354-199x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"199\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\nFor me, this poster addressed many of the issues I was talking about. This was a piece of software that would output a \"design\". It was based on many rules, but these rules were open, dynamic. This one system had thousands, perhaps millions, of differente possibilities (<em>Had I created a million posters?</em>).\r\n\r\nSomehow, something was not right...','A Thesis Tragedy, Part 2: \"You don\'t understand me!\"','','pending','open','open','','a-thesis-tragedy-part-2-you-dont-understand-me','','','2012-08-27 16:16:32','2012-08-27 16:16:32','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?p=819',0,'post','',0),(820,1,'2012-08-23 14:38:50','2012-08-23 14:38:50','After my brief (and perhaps not so brief) falling in love with Lev, I now had to actually come up with a thesis. It was all very clear in my head, but apparently nowhere el