32','After myÂ candidacy review and a long summer rest, my thoughts have changed a lot. I have grown older and wiser (maybe not) and I now see things a bit differently.Â RebellingÂ against is a very important','A Thesis Tragedy, Part 3 âWe\'re all dinasoursâ','','inherit','open','open','','824-revision-5','','','2012-08-23 14:48:32','2012-08-23 14:48:32','',824,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/824-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(831,1,'2012-08-23 15:06:08','2012-08-23 15:06:08','The act of rebellion is an important, if not intrinsic part of human nature. You have to be an atheist first in order to be a good believer in God. Looking back, I think I was trying to rebel against many things. I was trying to rebelÂ againstÂ aÂ disciplineÂ that respects its past. I was rebelling\r\n\r\nAfter myÂ candidacy review and a long summer rest, my thoughts have changed a lot. I have grown older and wiser (maybe not) and I now see things a bit differently.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','A Thesis Tragedy, Part 3 âWe\'re all dinasoursâ','','inherit','open','open','','824-revision-6','','','2012-08-23 15:06:08','2012-08-23 15:06:08','',824,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/824-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(832,1,'2012-08-23 14:40:45','2012-08-23 14:40:45','After my brief (and perhaps not so brief) falling in love with Lev, I now had to actually come up with a thesis. It was all very clear in my head, but apparently nowhere else. I now had to explain my thesis idea to many people, many times. No one really understood what I was talking about. Was it me, or were these people just too 20th century for my forward-looking ideas? (yes, there was a bit of arrogance in all these statements!). I tried to explain to people that I wanted to design for databases. I explained to them how they worked in the web for example. \"So you want to design website?\". \"So you want to make templates?\". \"So you want to automate design?\". \"Is this an Artificial Intelligence project?\". At the end, after many attempts, it just became \"This doesn\'t make any sense!\".\r\n\r\nI now had a new challenge, \"How do I explain this to my classmates and professors?\". More importantly, the problem became another one, one that I was able to recognize myself. How can I establish a problem that is more in tune with graphic design? After a while, I felt that the problem I was proposing was not so much of a design problem and that the reason why no one was really understanding what I was trying to say was that it was not a problem that could be easilyÂ addressedÂ by graphic design. The solution was to fine tune my problem statement to designers.\r\n\r\nI then thought about how it was that I was going to accomplish this in terms of design. My conclusion, after a long time of thinking, was systems and rules. If there is a lot of data that needs to be designed and presented, the solution to a new approach to design more in sync withÂ technologyÂ and the way technology works is focusing, not on a single event of design, but on systems and rules. I would establish systems and rules that would address multiple contents.\r\n\r\nIn response to the monotony of web design and other types of design \"systems\", my systems and rules would be dynamic, they would be open. The same content could be shown in different ways according toÂ computationallyÂ open rules. Things such as randomness and encoding became very important parts of my ideas. As an example I created a \"dynamic\" poster. This poster has one design but many different outputs.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster2-e1333393857788.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-721\" title=\"SystemPoster2\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster2-e1333393857788-199x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"199\" height=\"300\" /></a>Â <a href=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster3-e1333393749822.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-722\" title=\"SystemPoster3\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster3-e1333393749822-199x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"199\" height=\"300\" /></a>Â <a href=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster-e1333393815354.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-720\" title=\"SystemPoster\" src=\"http://thejsj.com/portfolio/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/SystemPoster-e1333393815354-199x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"199\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\nFor me, this poster addressed many of the issues I was talking about. This was a piece of software that would output a \"design\". It was based on many rules, but these rules were open, dynamic. This one system had thousands, perhaps millions, of differente possibilities (<em>Had I created a million posters?</em>).\r\n\r\nSomehow, something was not right...','A Thesis Tragedy, Part 2: \"You don\'t understand me!\"','','inherit','open','open','','819-revision-3','','','2012-08-23 14:40:45','2012-08-23 14:40:45','',819,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/819-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(833,1,'2012-08-23 14:16:40','2012-08-23 14:16:40','It all started with Lev. At theÂ beginningÂ of my short stay in grad school, I knew I would have to come up with an idea for my thesis. This sounded a bit overwhelming. What could I work on for two year without getting bored? At some point, I decided to read \"The Language of New Media\". I felt I was reading a the HolyÂ Scriptures. What captured me about the book was that, in a world dominated by technology, few people were talking about how to integrate technology and design, how to make work that was in sync with our times, how to think about new media in a way that understood the increasing role of technology in our socities and work. I found a lot of answers in this book.\r\n\r\nI decided pretty quickly that this is what my thesis would be about.Â Specifically, I wanted to deal with databases. How do you design for databases? After a short time as a web designer, I became increasingly disillusioned by the practice of web design. Web design, as a field, was concerned mostly with the outer look of this piece and took very little concern with the content, the narrative behind what was being presented. I seemed to me that it was only concerned with the outer shell of it all. The database, Lev said, was the cultural form of our time. This is what my thesis was going to be about.\r\n\r\nFor me it was quite clear. Narrative was a thing of the past. Narrative was out, databases were in. Anyone who thought a narrative approach to design was \"the way to go\", was simply a 20th centuryÂ dinosaur.','A Thesis Tragedy, Part 1 \"Oh Lev, I love you\"','','inherit','open','open','','817-revision-2','','','2012-08-23 14:16:40','2012-08-23 14:16:40','',817,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/817-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(834,1,'2012-08-27 16:17:26','2012-08-27 16:17:26','<em>Difference and Repetition Reader Â· Giles Deleuze &amp; Difference and Repetition: A Readerâs Guide Â· Joe Hughes</em>\r\n\r\nThrough the work of Deleuze, I with to explore, from a metaphysical viewpoint, what it really means to be âdifferentâ. Deleuzeâs idea that identity is only a secondary quality, following difference drastically changes the scope of my thesis ideas. One of the main ideas behind my thesis is the problem of uniqueness in the Information Age, and Deleuzeâs ideas might shed some light on questioning what is uniqueness in the first place.\r\n\r\n<em>Programming Collective Intelligence: Building Smart Web 2.0 Applications Â·Toby Segaran</em>\r\n\r\nHaving read parts of this book before, I wish to further understand some of the methods and ideas proposed in it. The book deals with ways in which programming is able to extract meaningful information out of immense data sets. I see my thesis as a design equivalent of sorts, meant to questions how design can do similar things. I also wish to incorporate some of the technical aspects dealt in this book into my own projects.\r\n\r\n<em>Information Anxiety Â· Richard Saul Wurman</em>\r\n\r\nHaving read part of this book, I find Wurmanâs ideas very relevant to my own work. Wurman deals with the problem of too much information and deals with different ways to approach this problem. My thesis deals with a similar problem, mainly, the issue of uniqueness within âinformation overloadâ. Wurmanâs theories will be helpful in trying to explore alternative ways of visually exploring this problem.\r\n\r\n<em>The Information: A History, A Theory, A Flood Â· James Gleick</em>\r\n\r\nThe reason why I wish to include this book is because of its many historical references to the history of Information Theory. Including great scientists like Claude Shannon and many other previous precedents to Information Theory, I feel that this understanding the history of information and Information Theory might help me gain a deeper historical perspective of the Information Age that will help inform my visual work.','Thesis Reading List','','publish','open','open','','thesis-reading-list','','','2012-08-27 16:17:26','2012-08-27 16:17:26','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?p=834',0,'post','',0),(835,1,'2012-08-27 16:16:52','2012-08-27 16:16:52','','Thesis Reading List','','inherit','open','open','','834-revision','','','2012-08-27 16:16:52','2012-08-27 16:16:52','',834,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/834-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(836,1,'2012-08-27 16:18:17','2012-08-27 16:18:17','Forgetting is sometimes the best way to work on something. When you delegate a task to memory, you are able to keep only the important bits.\r\n\r\nThis summer, I completely forgot my thesis, which is probably the best thing I did. This summer, I worked for a data visualization firm called Fathom. The group consisted of a mix of designers, programmers and hybrids ( such as myself ) interested in data visualization through multiple mediums. I worked on many different projects, I learned many new things in terms of design, programming, business, etc. I was lucky enough to work with a group of very smart talented people who, for the most part, had very similar interests as I did. They were very much interested in design, programming, technology, the future and how it all came together.\r\n\r\nYet, there was one difference between them and me, or at least the version of me that wrote my thesis statement. These people told stories. They would say this themselves. Their work was about telling stories and making these stories understandable to people a constant conversation between the micro and the macro. Itâs very interesting how many times the word âstoryâ would pop up in conversation at a place where the last thing I thought they did was telling stories.\r\n\r\nData visualization never seemed to be about stories to me. On the contrary, it seemed to be directly opposed to stories. This crazy ideas I got from Lev, who wrote:\r\n\r\nâIndeed, after the death of God (Nietzche), the end of Grand Narratives of Enlightenment (Lyotard), and the arrival of the web (Tim Berners-Lee), the world appears to us and endless and unstructured collection of images, texts and other data records, it is only appropriate that we will be moved to model it as a databaseâ ( The Language of New Media, Lev Manovich )\r\n\r\nI loved this book, and this book inspired many of my thesis ideas, but this summer I arrived at the terrible conclusion my dear Lev was wrong. The fact that Nietzche found God dead in his basement didnât stop anyone from believing in God. The fact that Lyotard stumbled into progressâs, scienceâs a historyâs death certificates, hasnât stopped most people from believing in them. In the same way, the web and all of technology hasnât stopped us from believing in stories. We are still, most definitely, human and the language of stories is the language we speak best. We seek stories everywhere.\r\n\r\nFor a long time, I had being searching for a definition of design. Itâs very difficult to arrive at a satisfactory definition. Yet, this summer I was able to arrive at one. Design is about humanizing things, about making things for humans. Itâs about telling a story where there might not be one. Itâs about making one up if you have to!\r\n\r\nWhat has changed in my thesis thought? I want to make things more human. I want to tell stories. But, I want to tell stories that pertain to our times using data, rules, programming, systemsâ¦ If we live in a world dominated by data, databases and systems then how can we make them more human? How can we use design as a tool to highlight the uniqueness of a row in database? How can we make these systems tell stories?\r\n\r\nThe other issue I have become increasingly interested in is the issue of uniqueness. Uniqueness is very uncommon in the technological realm. Everything is uniform, everything has a default. Then, how can we use technology, systems and rules to design in a way that highlights the uniqueness of something? Is it possible to make a system that highlight the uniqueness of something?','Summer Reflection','','publish','open','open','','summer-reflection','','','2013-01-03 22:39:09','2013-01-03 22:39:09','',0,'http://thejsj.com/?p=836',0,'post','',0),(837,1,'2012-08-27 16:17:37','2012-08-27 16:17:37','','Auto Draft','','inherit','open','open','','836-revision','','','2012-08-27 16:17:37','2012-08-27 16:17:37','',836,'http://thejsj.com/uncategorized/836-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(839,1,'2012-08-27 16:18:28','2012-08-27 16:18:28','Forgetting is sometimes the best way to work on something. When you delegate a task to memory, you are able to keep only the important bits.\r\n\r\nThis summer, I completley forgot my thesis, which is probably the best thing I did. This summer, I worked for a data visualization firm called Fathom. The group consisted of a mix of designers, programmers and hybrids ( such as myself ) intrested in data visual